  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="SECTIONThinkingAboutIntegration">
    <title>Two <q>Ways of Thinking</q> About Integration: Summation vs. Antidifferentiation</title>
    <introduction>

      <p>
        Beginning in <xref ref="SECTIONHist-intr"></xref> we observed
        that when we think about differentiation it is helpful to view
        differentiation through either the lens of geometry (Leibniz),
        or the lens of dynamics (Newton), depending on the particular
        context.  Similarly the next section describes two different,
        but equilvalent, ways to <q>think about</q> integration. As
        before these two viewpoints are, more or less, equivalent, but
        they provide different insights. Some are easier to see
        through one lens, others through the other.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsection  xml:id="SUBSECTIONIntegrationAsASum">
      <title>Integration as  Summation</title>

      <p>
        Suppose a point, <m>P</m>, traces out a line segment of some
        unknown length, <m>x</m>.
      </p>

      <image source="IC/X0toX.png" width="35%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>

<!-- <remark>       -->
<!--         <p> -->
<!--           Notice that in this setting <m>x</m> represents the -->
<!--           <em>length</em> of the line segment which <m>P</m> has -->
<!--           traced out, and <m>P_0</m> represents the starting position -->
<!--           of the point, and <m>P</m> represents its current position. -->
<!--           In particular <m>x</m> is <em>not</em> the position -->
<!--           (coordinate) of <m>P</m> on the line. It can't be because we -->
<!--           have not specified an origin (zero) point from which to -->
<!--           measure position. -->
<!--         </p> -->
<!-- </remark> -->

      <p>
        In the sketch below  we suppose that the coordinate of <m>P</m> is
        <m>x_n</m>, and that the coordinate of <m>P_0</m> is
        <m>x_0</m>.

We next partition the line segment between <m>x_0</m>
        and <m>x_n</m> by selecting points <m>x_1</m>, <m>x_2</m>,
        <m>\ldots </m>, <m>x_{n-1}</m> such that 
<me>
x_0\lt x_1 \lt x_2 \lt \cdots \lt x_{n-1} \lt x_n
</me>.
</p>

      <figure  xml:id="FIGUREPartitionedInterval">
        <caption>
          A partitioned interval.<!--  Notice that we use <m>x_i</m> to -->
          <!-- represent both the position of a partition point and its -->
          <!-- coordinate. -->
</caption>
        <image source="IC/FTC1.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The partition points subdivide the interval <m>[x_0, x_n]</m>
         into subintervals.  We represent the length of the first
        subinterval of <m>x</m> with <m>\Delta x_1</m>, of the second
        with <m>\Delta x_2</m>, and so on.  In general
        <m>\Delta{x_i}</m> represents the length of the <m>i</m>th
        subinterval of <m>x</m>. Clearly the length of the line
        segment <m>[x_0, x_n]</m> is
        <md>
          <mrow>\Delta{x_1}\amp{}+\Delta{x_2}+\Delta{x_3} +\cdots  +\Delta{x_{n-1}}+\Delta{x_n}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp{} =  (x_1-x_0)+(x_2-x_1)+(x_3-x_2) +\cdots + (x_{n-1}-x_{n-2})+(x_n-x_{n-1})</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp{}=x_n-x_0</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp{}=x</mrow>
          </md>.
          If the subintervals are all the same length, say
          <m>\Delta{x}</m>, then we no longer need the subscripts to
          distinguish them so we could write
          <me> \underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
          copies}}=x_n-x_0=x</me>
          
          instead.  But this is cumbersome and we are far too lazy to write
          all of that each time we want to indicate such a sum.  Leibniz proposed using 
          the letter <q>S</q> (first letter of the word <q>sum</q>) to
          simplify the summation  notation. He would have written:

          <men xml:id="EQUATIONFinDiffSum">
            \int{}\Delta{x}=\underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
          copies}} = x_n-x_0 =x
</men>.
</p>

      <aside>
        <title>Historical Background</title>
        <p>
          Leibniz chose the letter <q>S</q> because
          it is the first letter of Latin word <foreign>summa</foreign>,
          from which we get the English word <q>sum.</q>
        </p>
        <p>
          To a modern eye the integral sign looks like a stylized
          letter <q>S,</q> and that is often how it is described. But
          it isn<rsq/>t stylized at all. In the seventeenth century a
          printed letter <q>S</q> typically had one of several forms,
          depending on where it appeared in a word.  One of these
          extended above and below the line of text, much as the
          letter <q>f</q> extends above and the letter <q>j</q>
          extends below the line of text.  Leibniz adopted this doubly
          extended form of <q>S</q> as his summation sign. So the
          integral symbol isn<rsq/>t a stylized <q>S</q> at all.  It is an 
          archaic letter <q>S</q>.
        </p>
      </aside>

      <p> 
<idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Integral and the Integral Sign</h></idx>
        We assume, with Leibniz, that <xref
        ref="EQUATIONFinDiffSum">equation</xref> remains true when the finite
        differences (<m>\Delta{x}</m>) are replaced with infinitesimal
        differences (<m>\dx{x}{}</m>): <men
        xml:id="EQUATIONDefInt2">\int{\dx{x} }=x_n-x_0=x</men>.
        The symbol 
        <q><m>\int </m></q> is called an 
        <term>integral sign</term>, and any expression starting with 
        <q><m>\int </m> </q> and ending with 
        <q><m>\dx{x} </m></q> is called an 
        <term>integral</term>. 
      </p>
<remark>
<title>Finite vs. Infinitesimal Summation</title>
<p>
For Leibniz the distinction between the summation of infinitesimals
and of very small but finite real numbers, was somewhat blurred. Thus
he used <q><m>\dx{x}</m></q>  and <q><m>\Delta{x} </m></q>
 more or less interchangebly.
</p>
<p>
But we will need to keep them distinct. In modern times it has become
customary to distinguish finite and infinitesimal sums by using
different alphabets. Since <m>\Delta </m> comes from Greek, and
<m>\int </m> comes from Latin we extend this convention to 
summation by writing <xref ref="EQUATIONFinDiffSum">equation </xref>
as
          <me>
            \sum{}\Delta{x}=\underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
          copies}} = x_n-x_0 =x
</me>
because <q><m>\Sigma </m></q> is the Greek version of the Latin capital letter
<q>S</q>.

</p>
</remark>


      <p>
        <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">Equation</xref> is the simplest
        possible integral. It says that if we add up the lengths of
        all of the differentials that make up the line segment from
        <m>x_0</m> to <m>x_n</m> we will get its length,
        <m>x_n-x_0=x</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <idx><h>Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</h></idx>

        This is surely not surprising to you and you are probably
        wondering why we've taken the trouble to wrap such an obvious
        statement in this arcane notation. The reason is this: <xref
        ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref> is a very simple form of
        what is known as the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus which we
        will need to become very comfortable with. Later, when things
        get complex, it will be helpful to refer back to <xref
        ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref> and remind ourselves
        that, at its heart, integration is about adding up
        differentials.
      </p>

      <paragraphs  xml:id="PARAGRAPHCoordinatesAndVariables">
        <title>DIGRESSION: Coordinates and  Variable Names</title>
        <p>
          <!-- You may also be wondering why we are being so punctilious about -->
          <!-- distinguishing the label of a point <m>P</m>, and its coordinate -->
          <!-- <m>x_n</m>.  -->
          In <xref ref="FIGUREPartitionedInterval"></xref> we were
          rather careless about the distinction between the label of a
          point, e.g.  <m>P</m> or <m>P_0</m>, and its coordinate,
          e.g. <m>x_1</m> or <m>x_2</m>. A natural question would be
          <q>Aren<rsq/>t they the same thing?</q>
        </p>
        <p> No, actually they aren<rsq/>t. The label of a point is the
        name we use to distinguish it from other points. The
        (horizontal) coordinate of a point is it<rsq/>s (horizontal)
        distance from the origin.  Consider the following diagram.<!--
        Suppose <m>P</m> is a point on -->
        <!-- the <m>x</m>-axis located at a distance of <m>x</m> to the right of -->
        <!-- the origin. Does <m>x</m> represent a length? If so, what is <m>x</m> -->
        <!-- the length of? -->
        </p>
        <image source="IC/VarX2.png" width="60%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          The labels (names) of the two points are <m>P_0</m> and <m>P</m>. Since
          <m>x_0</m> measures the distance between zero and <m>P_0</m> it is by
          definition the coordinate of the point labeled <m>P_0</m>.  Similarly <m>x_n</m> is the coordinate of <m>P</m>.
        </p>
        <aside>
          <title>Comment</title>
          <p>
            If a vertical axis were present zero would be the second
            coordinate of both points. Do you see why?
          </p>
        </aside>

        <p>
          On the
          other hand since <m>x</m> <mdash/> the distance between <m>P_0</m> and
          <m>P</m> <mdash/> is not measured from the origin it is
          neither a coordinate nor the label of a point. 
          <!-- <p> -->
          <!-- Do you see -->
          <!-- what<rsq/>s going on here? The cooordinate <m>x</m> is indeed the length of the line segment between the origin and <m>P</m>. By definition every coordinate is the length of a line segment. But not every length  is necessarily a cooordinate. To see why consider the following sketch.  -->
          <!-- </p> -->
          <!-- <image source="IC/VarX2.png" width="60%"> -->
          <!-- <shortdescription></shortdescription> -->
          <!-- </image> -->
          <!-- <p> -->
          <!-- In this case <m>P</m> and <m>P_0</m> are the labels of the two points, -->
          <!-- whereas <m>x_n</m> and <m>x_0</m> are their coordinates, respectively. -->
          <!-- </p> -->
          It is the length of the line segment
          <m>\overline{P_0P}</m>. If we partition this line segment and
          compute <m>\int\dx{x} </m> we get 
          <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since their coordinates distinguish one point from another
          as well as their labels do, a (very) common practice is to
          dispense with the labels altogether and make the coordinates
          serve both purposes as in the diagram below.
        </p>
        <image source="IC/VarX3.png" width="60%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          Strictly speaking this is an abuse of our notation and it can cause
          confusion because it isn<rsq/>t always clear whether <m>x_0</m> and
          <m>x_n</m> refer to points on the line, or their distance from the
          origin (their coordinates). Always be sure it is clear to you which
          usage is intended.
        </p>

        <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
      </paragraphs>
    </subsection>

    <subsection  xml:id="SECTIONIntAsAntiDiff">
      <title>Integration as Antidifferentiation</title>

      <definition  xml:id="DEFINITIONAntiderivative">
        <title>Antiderivative</title>
<idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Antiderivative</h></idx>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose we have a function <men
            xml:id="EQUATIONDefAntideriv">y=F(t)</men> with derivative
            <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=F^\prime(t)=f(t)</m>. Then <m>F(t)</m> is
            called an <term>antiderivative</term> of <m>f(t)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        From <xref ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref> , we
        see that
        
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntAsAntiDiff">\dx{y}=F^\prime(t)\dx{t}=f(t)\dx{t}</men>.

</p>
<p>


 We know from our work in
        <xref ref="SUBSECTIONIntegrationAsASum"></xref> (specifically
        <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref>) that
        
        <me>y=\int\dx{y}</me>.

        So if we sum all of the differentials on the left and right sides of <xref ref="EQUATIONIntAsAntiDiff">equation</xref>  we have

        <me>y=\int\dx{y}= \int f(t)\dx{t}</me>.
          Observe that since <m>\dx{y} </m> is a differential it follows
          that <m>f(t)\dx{t}</m> is also a differential so the expression
          <m>\int f(t)\dx{t}</m> is a valid integral.

      </p>



      <p>
        Thus it appears that if <m>\dx{y}=f(t)\dx{t} </m> is known
        then <m>y=F(t)</m> will be the antiderivative of
        <m>f(t)</m>. That is to say, integration appears to be
        <q>differentiation run backwards.</q> This seems reasonable
        since differentiation consists of subtracting (finding
        differentials) and integration consists of adding (summing
        differentials). Addition and subtraction can  both be thought of as <q>doing the the other backwards.</q>

      </p>

      <p>
        It follows immediately from <xref
        ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref> and the <xref
        ref="THEOREMConstRule">Constant Rule</xref> that if a function has one antiderivative
        then it has infinitely many.  That is, if <m>F(x)</m> is an antiderivative of
        <m>f(x)</m> then so is <m>F(x)+5</m>. And <m>F(x)+80</m>. In
        fact if <m>C</m> ia a constant then so is <m>F(x)+C</m> for
        every possible value of <m>C</m>
        because we get a (slightly) different antiderivative
        each time we add a constant to <m>F(x)</m>.  
</p>
<p>
Thus if
        we know  one antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m>,
        then we know all (infinitely many) of the antiderivatives of
        <m>f(x)</m>.
        Remember this. We
        will return to it when we discuss <xref ref="THEOREMFTC"></xref> below.
      </p>

      <example xml:id="EXAMPLESimpleInt1">
        <title>A Simple Integration</title>
        <p>
          For example, can you find a formula for this integral:
          <me>\int2t\dx{t}</me>?
        </p>
        <p>
          Clearly <m>f(t)=2t</m> so from <xref
          ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref> we see that <m>F(t) =
          t^2</m> is one antiderivative, and we can capture all of the
          antiderivatives by adding an arbitrary constant. Thus
          <me>\int 2t\dx{t} = t^2 + C</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
<idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Antiderivative</h><h>most general</h></idx>
           This shows that the expression <m>\int f(t)\dx{t} </m>
           represents a multifunction much like the <q>
           <m>\text{arc}</m></q> functions we encountered in <xref
           ref="CHAPTERcalc-trig"></xref>.  However, none of the
           complicated domain and range difficulties that caused so
           many headaches in <xref
           ref="SECTIONinverse-tan-and-cot"></xref> will be in play
           here. Since the multifunctions arising from integration are
           relatively simple, we will dispense with the formal language and
           call <me>F(t) = \int 2t\dx{t} = t^2+C</me> the <term>most general
           antiderivative</term> of <m>f(t) = t^2</m>.<!--  But remember -->
           <!-- that it is really a multifunction since <q><m>C</m></q> is -->
           <!-- unspecified. -->  There will be times when we will want to
           choose only one of the functions represented by <m>\int
           f(t)\dx{t}</m>. This will consist entirely of choosing the
           value of <m>C</m> that works for the problem in front of us.
        </p>
      </example>

      <p>
        Beginning in  the early twentieth century integration theory has grown considerably beyond
        what we will be learning in this course. But the underlying
        notions of the integral as a sum and the integral as an
        antiderivative are still very helpful and we will rely on them
        rather heavily, at least at first.
      </p>


      <exercise xml:id="EXERCISEAntiDerivPractice">
            <idx><h>Antiderivative</h></idx>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Show that  the following statements are true. Assume
            <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant.

            (We have not shown you how to compute any of these
            integrals. But  you know how to differentiate. Read <xref
            ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref>  again carefully.)
</p>


        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int 2te^{t^2}\dx{t} = e^{t^2} +C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int te^t\dx{t} = (t-1)e^t+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int \sin(x)\cos(x)\dx{x} =\frac12\sin^2(x)+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              Notice that we<rsq/>ve used <m>x</m> instead of <m>t</m> for our
              variable. Does that matter? Explain.
            </p>
          </hint>
        </task>
        <task  xml:id="PROBLEMSinsqcossqantider">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int \sin(\theta )\cos(\theta )\dx{\theta } =
              -\frac12\cos^2(\theta )+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int u\cos(u) \dx{u} = u\sin(u)+\cos(u)+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int x\ln(x) \dx{x} = x(\ln{x}-1)+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>


      </exercise>

<p>
The exercises in <xref ref="PROBLEMAntiDiffPractice"></xref> were all
a bit contrived. Since we gave you the antiderivatives you don<rsq/>t
really need to know how tho integrate.
</p>
<p>
 The real question here is <q>How could you find these antiderivatives
 if we hadn<rsq/>t given them to you?</q>
</p>

    </subsection>

<conclusion>

        <title>We Integrate Differentials, Not Functions</title>
        <p>
          Integration can be usefully thought of as either summation or
          antidifferentiation. We will flip between these two mindsets as
          convenient in much the same way that we flipped between the
          dynamic (Newtonian) and geometric (Leibnizian) viewpoints in
          <xref ref="DiffCalcFromPractice"></xref>.
        </p>
<p>
Since it is valid to think of <m>\int
f(x)\dx{x}</m> as representing an antiderivative of the function
<m>f</m> it is customary to speak these symbols aloud as <q>the integral of <m>f</m>
of <m>x</m>.</q> While this is not wrong, it is not quite right
either. Properly speaking, we should say <q>the integral of the
differential <m>f(x)</m> times <m>\dx{x}</m>.</q> But no one does that
so we won<rsq/>t either.
</p>
<p>
But if we (the authors or your instructor) consistently speak
incorrectly (as we tend to do in this instance) it is easy for 
you (the student) to develop  unfortunate habits of mind. 
We will take a moment to try to  prevent that from happening.
</p>
        <p>
         The integral sign was designed (by Leibniz) to indicate summation, not
          antidifferentiation. As a result it is very easy to use it improperly. Sooner or later most people
          will fall into the habit of dropping the final
          <q><m>\dx{x}</m>,</q>  of writing <m>\int f(x)</m> instead of
          <m>\int f(x)\dx{x}</m>, and then calling them both the integral
          of the function <m>f(x)</m>.
</p>
<p>
 This is an unfortunate, but
          common, abuse of the notation.  You can not integrate a
          function, only a differential. We <em>strongly</em> suggest
          that you take care to avoid this bad habit for as long as
          you can because it can be very confusing. Especially when
          the concepts are new.
        </p>
        <p>
          Remember that <me>\int f(x)</me> is meaningless no matter how
          convenient it might be because it indicates that we are summing
          a function, not a differential.
        </p>
<aside>
          <title>Notation</title>
          <p>
            By calling <m>\int f(x)</m> meaningless we have overstated
            the situation a bit. If you study mathematics long enough
            you will encounter situations where <m>\int{f(x)}</m> is a
            perfectly reasonable notation to use. But we will not
            encounter them here, and it is best if you don<rsq/>t fall
            into this habit while you are still learning the basics.
          </p>
</aside>


        <p>
          But the meaning of <me>\int
          f(x)\dx{x}</me> is clear. We're summing up all of the
          differentials of the form <m>f(x)\dx{x} </m>.
        </p>

<p>
Finally, there is a puzzle here. In <xref
ref="SUBSECTIONIntegrationAsASum"></xref> we introduced
integration as summation, and we invented the integral sign
<m>\left(\int{}\right)</m> to reflect that idea. But in this section we have
reinterpreted the integral to mean antidifferentiation and the idea of
<q>integral as summation</q> seems to have died a quiet death. Nowhere in
<xref ref="EXAMPLESimpleInt1"></xref> does a summation appear. 
</p>
<p>
But this is the point. Computing the sum <m>\int f(x)\dx{x}</m>  is a
very daunting task. Where would you even begin? By reinterpreting it
as an antidifferentiation problem we are able to find the sum,
<m>F(x)</m> without the bother of adding up 
(infinitely many) differentials of the form
<m>f(x)\dx{x}</m>. Antidifferentiation gives us a way to compute the
sum indirectly.
</p>
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!--   Suppose that <m>y=t^2</m> then <m>\dx{y} =2t\dx{t}</m>. Then -->
        <!--   <m>\int 2t\dx{t}</m> makes sense because the product -->
        <!--   <m>2t\dx{t}=\dx{y}</m> is a differential. But <m>\int 2t</m> -->
        <!--   is nonsense because <m>2t</m> alone is not a differential. -->
        <!-- </p> -->
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!--   In particular, <m>\int 2t</m> is meaningless. However  if <m>y=t^2</m> -->
        <!--   then what is probably meant is -->
        <!--   <men  xml:id="EQUATIONPlusCMissing">\int 2t\dx{t} = \int \dx{y}</men> which is equal to <m>y</m> since <m>\int \dx{y}</m> means  -->
        <!--   <q>add up the differentials of <m>y</m>.</q> -->
        <!-- </p> -->

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   But remember that the title of this -->
      <!--   chapter is <q>Integration in its <em>Simplest</em> Form.</q> Running -->
      <!--   differentiation backwards is not as straightforward as it first -->
      <!--   appears to be. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
</conclusion>


  </section>

  <section  xml:id="SECTIONIntegrationRules1">
    <title>Rules for Integration</title>
    <p>
      Since integration can be thought of as the reverse of
      differentiation it is not too surprising to learn that each
      differentiation rule has its counterpart as an integration rule.
      The following list illustrates some of the rules we already know
      from Differential Calculus in both their differential and
      integral form.

  <mdn>
    <mrow number="no">
      \text{Differentiation}\text{ Rule}\amp{}\amp{}\text{Integration} \text{ Rule}
    </mrow>
  </mdn>

<mdn>


    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleConstant">
      \dx(\text{constant})=0;\amp{}\amp{}\int0\dx{x}=C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleSum">
      \dx(f+g)=\dx{f}+\dx{g};\amp{}\amp{}\int\dx(f+g)=f+g+C
<!-- \int\dx{f}+\int\dx{g} -->
    </mrow>
<!-- <mrow> -->
<!-- \amp{}\amp{}=f+g+C -->
<!--     </mrow> -->
</mdn>

<mdn>

<mrow number="no">
      \text{If }a\text{ is constant, then }          
    </mrow>
    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleConstMult">
\dx(ay)=a\dx(y);\amp{}\amp{}\int a\dx{y}<!-- =\int\dx(ay) -->=a\int\dx{y}=ay+C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleMonomial">
      \dx(x^{n+1})=(n+1)x^n\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int x^n\dx{x} = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+C, n\neq
      -1
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleOneOver">
      \dx(\ln(x))<!-- =\frac1x\dx{x} -->=x^{-1}\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int x^{-1}\dx{x} = \ln\abs{x}+C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleExp">
      \dx(e^x)= e^x\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int e^x\dx{x} = e^x+C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleCos">
      \dx(\sin(x))=\cos(x)\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int \cos(x)\dx{x} = \sin(x) +C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleSin">
      \dx(\cos(x))=-\sin(x)\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int \sin(x)\dx{x} = -\cos(x) +C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleTan">
      \dx(\tan(x))=\sec^2(x)\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int\sec^2(x)\dx{x} = \tan(x)+C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleSec">
      \dx(\sec(x))= \sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int\sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x}=\sec(x)+C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleInvSin">
      \dx(\inverse\sin(x))=
      \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sin(x)+C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleInvTan">
      \dx(\inverse\tan(x))=   \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}=\inverse\tan(x)+C
    </mrow>
</mdn>

<mdn>

    <mrow xml:id="IntRuleInvSec">
      \dx(\inverse\sec(x))=    \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}
      ;\amp{}\amp{}\int\frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sec(x)+C
    </mrow>
</mdn>
    </p>





    <!-- <table xml:id="TABLEBasicIntegration"> -->
    <!--   <title>Integration Rules Inherited from Differentiation Rules</title> -->
    <!--   <tabular halign="center"> -->
