    <!--     </row> -->
    <!--     <row> -->
    <!--       <cell>10</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\sec(x))= \sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x}</m></cell> -->
    <!--       <cell><m>\displaystyle\int\sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x}=\sec(x)+C</m></cell> -->
    <!--     </row> -->
    <!--     <row> -->
    <!--       <cell>11</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sin(x))= -->
    <!--       \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}</m></cell> -->
    <!--       <cell><m>\displaystyle\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sin(x)+C</m></cell> -->
    <!--     </row> -->
    <!--     <row> -->
    <!--       <cell>12</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\tan(x))= -->
    <!--       \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}</m></cell> -->
    <!--       <cell><m>\displaystyle\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}=\inverse\tan(x)+C</m></cell> -->
    <!--     </row> -->
    <!--     <row> -->
    <!--       <cell>13</cell>          <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sec(x))= -->
    <!--       \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}</m></cell> -->
    <!--       <cell><m>\displaystyle\int\frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sec(x)+C</m></cell> -->
    <!--     </row> -->
    <!--   </tabular> -->
    <!-- </table> -->
    
    

    
    
    <problem xml:id="DRILLIntSum">
      <p>
        <xref
        ref="IntRuleSum" >Integration Rules</xref> and <xref
        ref="IntRuleConstMult"></xref> appear to violate <xref
        ref="IntRuleConstant">Integration Rule</xref>, don<rsq/>t
they?   Isn<rsq/>t it true that
        <me>
        \int\dx(f+g)=  \int \dx{f} +\int \dx{g} = f+C_1+g+C_2
        </me>
        where <m>C_1</m> and <m>C_2</m> are arbitrary constants, and that
        <me>
          a\int\dx{y}=a(y+c)=ay+aC </me>.
          Explain how <xref
        ref="IntRuleSum" >Integration Rules</xref> and <xref
        ref="IntRuleConstMult"></xref> are legitimate as stated.
      </p>
    </problem>
    
    <p>
      In light of <xref ref="DRILLIntSum"></xref>, it is common
      practice integrate each term of a differential and then combine
      all of the arbitrary constants into a single constant.
    </p>
<example>
  <p>
For example,
      consider
      
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \int\left(5x^2-3\sqrt{x}+\frac{2}{1+x^2}\right)\amp{}\dx{x}
        </mrow>
      <mrow>
          \amp{}=5\int x^2\dx{x}-3\int x^\frac12
          \dx{x}+2\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp =5\left(\frac{x^3}{3}\right) +C_1-
          \frac{3\left(x^{\frac12}\right)}{\frac32} + C_2 +
          2\inverse\tan(x)+C_3
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          \amp =\frac53x^3-2x^{\frac32}+2\inverse\tan(x)+C
        </mrow>
      </md>,
where <m>C=C_1+C_2+C_3</m>.
  </p>
</example>
<p>
      As with differentiation, when you get more comfortable
      with integration, you will probably do many of these steps in your
      head.  But that ability will only come with practice.
    </p>

      <problem  xml:id="PROBLEMAntiDiffPractice">
        <p>
          Use <xref first="IntRuleConstant"
          last="IntRuleInvSec">Integration Rules</xref>  to find the most
          general antiderivative.
          <ol cols="2" marker="i">
            <li>
              <m>\int t^2\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int 3t-2\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int 7\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \sin(t)\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int 5\cos(t)\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \sec(t)\tan(t)\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int t + e^t\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \frac{1}{1+\theta^2}\dx{\theta{}}</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>


    <p>
      Conspicuously absent from our list of rules are the integral
      form of the Product Rule, the Quotient Rule, and the Chain Rule.
      The reverse of the Quotient Rule is rather limited in its
      applicability and typically is not used.  Reversing the others
      can be quite useful but we are not quite ready to discuss them
      in depth. 
    </p>

<!-- <paragraphs> -->
<!-- <!-\- <title>The Integral <m>\displaystyle\int \frac1x \dx{x}</m> and -\-> -->
<!-- <!-\- Absolute Value</title> -\-> -->
<!-- <title> -->
<!-- <xref ref="IntRuleOneOver">Integration Rule</xref> -->
<!-- </title> -->
<paragraphs>
<title>A Few Comments on  <xref ref="IntRuleOneOver">Integration Rule</xref>  </title>

    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration">>Table</xref> is not -->
    <!--   exhaustive. It couldn<rsq/>t possibly be since every -->
    <!--   differentiation formula gives rise to a corresponding -->
    <!--   integration formula. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <p>
First,      notice that <xref ref="IntRuleMonomial">Integration Rule</xref>  will work if the
      exponent has any value 
<em>except</em> <m>n=-1</m>. If we try to apply it we<rsq/>ll get 
<me>
\int \inverse{x}\dx{x} = \frac{x^{1-1}}{1-1} = \frac{1}{0}
</me> 
which we know is meaningless.
</p>
<p>
For this
single exception we have to turn to <xref ref="IntRuleOneOver">Integration Rule</xref>:
<m>\int\frac1x\dx{x}=\ln\abs{x}+C{}</m>. 
    </p>
<p>
Does it seem strange to you that there would be this single exception
to <xref ref="IntRuleMonomial">Integration Rule</xref>? Us too.
</p>
    
        <p>
 Also notice the absolute value in the formula:
          <me>
            \int\inverse x\dx{x}=\ln\abs{x}+C.
          </me> 
        </p>
        <p>
          We saw in <xref ref="DIGRESSIONAbsValSqrt" text="custom">DIGRESSION: The Absolute Value Function</xref>  that an
          alternative definition of the absolute value function is
          <me>\abs{x}=\sqrt{x^2}</me>.
        </p>
    <exercise>
<statement>
        <p>
          Show that if we differentiate the definition <m>\ln(x)
          =\sqrt{x^2}</m> we still obtain the formula
          <me>
            \dx(\ln\abs{x})=\frac1x \dx{x}
            </me>.
        </p>
</statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Be careful that you do not try to take the logarithm of a
          negative number.
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>
        <p>
          It is common (though incorrect) practice to disregard the
          absolute value and  write <m>\int\inverse
          x\dx{x}=\ln(x)+C</m>, even though this is only valid for
          <m>x\gt{0}</m>.  We will also adopt this practice but you
          should always bear in mind that there are situations where
          the absolute value must be used. 
        </p>
</paragraphs>

    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   If you read each of these Differentiation and Integration Rules -->
    <!--   verbally you can hear that they reverse each other. For example in -->
    <!--   line 4 we see that to differentiate <m>x</m> to a power, we -->
    <!--   <q>multiply by the exponent and then subtract one from the -->
    <!--   exponent.</q> To reverse the process notice that everything gets run -->
    <!--   backwards: We first <q>add one to the exponent, then we divide by -->
    <!--   the exponent.</q> (In the same way that when dressing you put your -->
    <!--   socks on and then your shoes and to reverse it you take off your -->
    <!--     shoes first and then your socks). -->
    <!-- </p> -->
  </section>

</chapter>
